[EN]
# The Public Notebook

## 1. Writing for the Future Interviewer
I often revisit my own blog posts. Not out of narcissism, but out of necessity.
I am writing this blog primarily for one person: **Future Me**, sitting in an interview room.

Technical interviews are not just about LeetCode; they are about the narrative. When an interviewer asks, *"Tell me about a time you failed and how you handled it,"* or *"How do you learn new technologies?"*, I don't want to give a generic answer.
I want to have "receipts."
These English posts are my documentation. They record the confusion of KMP algorithms, the exhaustion of the Java crash course, and the discipline of 16-hour coding sessions.
By articulating my thought process now, I am preparing the script for my future career.

[END]

[ZH]
# 公开的笔记本

## 1. 写给未来的面试官看
我时常会翻看自己的博客。这不是自恋，而是刚需。
我写这些博客，主要是一个为了一个人：**坐在面试房间里的“未来的我”**。

技术面试不只是考 LeetCode，更是考故事线。当面试官问：*“讲讲你遇到过的挫折以及你是如何处理的”*，或者*“你是如何学习新技术的”*，我不想给出一个通用的模版答案。
我要拿出“证据”。
这些英文博文就是我的文档。它们记录了我在 KMP 算法上的困惑，在 Java 快进班里的精疲力竭，以及连续 16 小时编程的自律。
现在把思维过程清晰地写下来，我其实是在为我未来的职业生涯写剧本。
[END]

[EN]
## 2. Writing for the Peer Pressure
The secondary reason is for my peers—my classmates and friends here in Ireland.
This is why I write in Chinese.
I share my struggles and my small wins to create a system of **Accountability**.
If I post about mastering a specific algorithm, I cannot afford to fail at it in class the next day.
If I write about my "growth mindset," I cannot be caught complaining about difficulties.

By making my goals and progress public, I invite pressure.
Most people avoid pressure; I engineer it.
This external "gaze" from my peers forces me to stay consistent. It turns the abstract goal of "studying hard" into a tangible social contract.

[END]

[ZH]
## 2. 写给同伴压力
第二个原因是为了我的同伴——我在爱尔兰的同学和朋友们。
这也是我保留中文部分的原因。
我分享我的挣扎和小小的胜利，是为了建立一个**“问责系统”**。
如果我发博客说我搞懂了某个算法，我就不能允许自己在第二天的课上还要露怯。
如果我大谈“成长型思维”，我就不能被发现在面对困难时抱怨连天。

通过公开我的目标和进度，我在主动邀请压力。
大多数人通过回避压力来寻求舒适，而我通过设计压力来驱动自己。
这种来自同伴的“注视”，逼迫我保持一致性。它把“努力学习”这个抽象的目标，转化成了一种有形的社会契约。
[END]

[EN]
## 3. The Documentation of a Transformation
In my previous life as a lawyer, everything had to be written down to be valid.
Here, in Computer Science, it is the same.
If I solved a bug but didn't understand *why*, I didn't solve it.
If I lived through a transformation but didn't record *how*, the lessons fade.

So I write.
I write to verify my understanding.
I write to lock in the memories.
I write so that when I look back, I don't just see the result; I see the trajectory.

[END]

[ZH]
# 3. 记录一场蜕变
在我作为律师的前半生里，一切凡事必须“落笔”才算数。
在这里，在计算机科学的世界里，也是一样。
如果我解决了一个 Bug 却不知道*为什么*，那我不算解决。
如果我经历了一场蜕变却没记录*如何*发生的，那些教训就会褪色。

所以我写作。
我写作是为了验证我的理解。
我写作是为了锁定那些记忆。
我写作，是为了当我回首时，我看到的不仅仅是结果，而是清晰的弹道轨迹。
[END]